There are some difference between the book and this movie, but it brings the story to life vividly.

It begins with Bella's Birthday Party.  An accident caused Bella to have a major cut on her arm.  Though all, but Jasper, resisted;  the blood instantly turned the Cullens, from a Sweat Family, to Ravenous Vampires.

That was enough to convince Edward he needed to leave Bella.  Edward revered humans.  He's clearly More than Human, and believes himself Less than Human.  He deliberately breaks Bella's heart, hoping she'd get over him and live a normal life.  Obviously that doesn't work!

Bella spends most of the movie lost.  She believes the lie, believes she's unworthy of Edward.  With him gone she was stuck never moving forward.  She couldn't live without her memories of him, without knowing he was somewhere in the world.  At the same time thinking about him was too painful to endure.  Throughout all that, at some level, she clearly knew Edward had never stopped loving her.

Throughout most of the movie Bella pursued more and more dangerous activities.  Risking her life repeatedly.  Though she wasn't consciously trying to kill herself, yet, she hadn't any reason to live.  Even falling for Jacob wasn't enough to heel Bella.  On many levels she clearly wanted to die, to end the pain.

Next is Bella and Edward's reunion under the clock tower.  The dialogue is different than the book, but the emotion is the same.  For over 6 Months, both had been completely dead inside.  Once back in each others arms, both were alive again.

The ending has the Volturi threatening them if Bella doesn't become a Vampire.  The Wolves threatening to kill them if she does become a Vampire.  Edward still thinking she's better off as a Human.  And neither Bella nor Edward really cared about any of that.  All that mattered was they together.

Twilight Forever!

I bought this movie for my girlfriend because she is a book nerd and has to read the book before she sees the movie so it makes sense. She doesn't always say the book was better. Sometimes she likes the movie better. In this case, she thought they complemented each other. The movie follows the book closely. It has to condense some for time allowed, that why so many movies are cut up in two parts these days. The YA genre is full of paranormal romance. This story was a refreshing spin off the usual formula of teen angst with supernatural/futuristic elements. I have to say, that I watched it too and while I wasn't as engrossed in it as my girlfriend was, it was easy to follow, well-written, and had a strong leading player. I recommend this movie whether you have read the book or not.
